JOHANNESBURG - The strike by Post Office and Telkom workers is entering its second week, with workers demanding a 12 percent wage increase. The Post Office so far offering 6 percent, and Telkom 3 percent. The Communication Workers Union (CWU) says members have been fighting for a wage increase for over three years. READ:Â Post Office, Telkom workers vow to fight to the end On Friday, the CWU rallied workers ahead of another strike, this time at MTN's Johannesburg headquarters. This follows the union's meetings earlier this week with the Post Office and Telkom to discuss wage increases. The union expressed empathy for social-grant beneficiaries affected by the ongoing Post Office-worker strike. The CWU says it's set to meet with the Post Office and Telkom to discuss the way forward. eNCA